Helper functions¶

  • return_ga_traj returns the tiny golden angle kspace trajectory
In [7]:
def return_ga_traj(nX, ntviews, tiny_num=7):
    """Returns tiny golden angle trajectory and density compensation

    Parameters
    ----------
    nX : int
        number of readout points
    ntviews : int
        number of radial spokes/turns
    tiny_num : int
        type of golden angle, e.g. 7 for 7th tiny golden angle

    Returns
    -------
    traj : ndarray
        trajectory with shape (nX, ntviews)
    densitycomp : ndarray

    Reference
    ---------
    https://doi.org/10.1002/mrm.25831

    """
    golden_ratio = (np.sqrt(5.0) + 1.0) / 2.0
    golden_angle = np.pi / (golden_ratio + tiny_num - 1)

    radian = np.mod(np.arange(0, ntviews) * golden_angle, 2. * np.pi)
    rho = np.arange(-np.floor(nX / 2), np.floor(nX / 2)) + 0.5

    _sin = np.sin(radian)
    _cos = np.cos(radian)

    # Complex trajectory
    traj = np.stack(((rho[..., np.newaxis] * _sin[np.newaxis, ...]),
                     (rho[..., np.newaxis] * _cos[np.newaxis, ...])), axis=2)
    
    # Density Compensation
    densitycomp = np.sqrt(np.power(traj[...,0], 2) + np.power(traj[...,1], 2))
    densitycomp /= densitycomp.max()
    
    # Reshape into (n_spokes, n_readout, 2)
    traj = traj.transpose((1,0,2))
    
    # Reshape into (n_spokes, n_readout)
    densitycomp = densitycomp.transpose((1,0))
    
    return traj, densitycomp

Create a radial trajectory based off of the nyquist rate¶

  • nyquist criteria for radial trajectories is $\frac{\textrm{N}\pi}{2}$, where $\textrm{N}$ is the number of lines required for fully-sampled data in cartesian sampling. In this case, it is equal to n_ro.
In [8]:
ntviews = int(np.pi*n_ro/2)

# Get the 7th tiny golden angle k-space trajectory and density compensation
traj, dc = return_ga_traj(nX=n_ro, ntviews=ntviews)

n_ro, ntviews, traj.shape, dc.shape

  • Use the golden-angle radial trajectory and the non-uniform FFT operator to transform the image into non-cartesian k-space

NUFFT = sigpy.linop.NUFFT(ishape=square_cine[np.newaxis,...].shape,
                          coord=traj)
# Apply the operator to transform the image into non-cartesian k-space
ksp_radial = NUFFT*square_cine[np.newaxis,...] # add a singleton dimension to the front to confirm with sigpy conventions

Visualize the non-cartesian k-space data¶

  • this would be similar to what we'd get out of an MRI machine that was scanning using a non-cartesian radial trajectory with a single coil
  • if you look at the 2nd subplot below, you'll notice that non-cartesian k-space data that's acquired with the MRI machine does not fall nicely on a grid
  • this is what makes the radial masks on fully-sampled cartesian data from the RefineGAN repository a little different than reality; with just the simple radial mask placed on top of fully sampled data, you're still using exact acquired data without any of the distortions that would've been introduced by interpolating acquired non-cartesian data onto a cartesian grid.

Reconstruct the image from the non-cartesian data¶

  • since the data does not fall on a neat uniformly spaced grid that's required for typical FFT reconstruction, we need to use the adjoint operator of the non-uniform FFT (NUFFT) to go from non-cartesian k-space to image space
In [11]:
# reconstruct the data by applying the non-uniform FFT operator on the density-compensated kspace data
back = NUFFT.H*(ksp_radial*dc)

# We can see what happens if we don't apply density-compensation to weigh down the oversampled low frequency data
# relative to the high frequency data --the image will be dominated by the oversampled low frequency data
back_no_density_compensation = NUFFT.H*ksp_radial

sigpy.plot.ImagePlot(back, x=1, y=2)
Out[11]:
<sigpy.plot.ImagePlot at 0x7fa971c4bd90>

Without density-compensation¶

  • radial k-space data without density compensation will be dominated by low-frequency content; back_no_density_compensation will have a blown out blurry look to it
  • this density-compensation is another aspect of non-cartesian radial k-space reconstruction that's not part of cartesian k-space reconstruction. the oversampling of low-frequency k-space is a feature of radial sampling.
In [12]:
sigpy.plot.ImagePlot(back_no_density_compensation, x=1, y=2)
Out[12]:
<sigpy.plot.ImagePlot at 0x7fa971853990>

Now bring the reconstructed image back into cartesian k-space¶

  • if we now take the density-compensated reconstructed image (i.e. the one derived from non-cartesian k-space data) and perform a standard FFT, we can get cartesian k-space data
  • recall that going from non-cartesian radial k-space data to cartesian k-space data requires a gridding operation that interpolates the radial data onto a cartesian grid. this interpolation does introduce some artifacts, since the data in this new cartesian k-space isn't the truly measured data from the coils-- they are the interpolated values onto the cartesian grid.
  • also note that radial k-space data does not extend all the radial spokes to the edges of the image, but appears as a circle inscribed inside a rectangle. this is another slight difference to the radial mask in RefineGAN.
In [13]:
cartesian_kspace = sigpy.fft(back)

sigpy.plot.ImagePlot(np.log(np.abs(cartesian_kspace)), x=1, y=2)
Out[13]:
<sigpy.plot.ImagePlot at 0x7fa9717fc890>

Finally, we can apply an inverse FFT to get back to image space¶

  • this will not be identical to the original square_cine image, since the non-cartesian gridding operations necessarily create new data that was not actually measured, but it should be pretty close
In [14]:
cartesian_image = sigpy.ifft(cartesian_kspace)
sigpy.plot.ImagePlot(cartesian_image, x=1, y=2)
Out[14]:
<sigpy.plot.ImagePlot at 0x7fa9718843d0>

Remarks¶

  • in this notebook, we only worked on a single frame from the cine and treated it as a single-coil acquisition
  • the next notebook will cover the case of multi-coil non-cartesian acquisition, with combination of the multi-coil data using SENSE type operators along with the coil sensitivity maps that we have calculated and dumped into the ocmr_intermediate.hdf5 container.
    • we'll also cover a more realistic scenario in which the different frames of the cine have different radial sampling patterns (e.g. different number of radial spokes with a more random mix of angles), as is typical in our cardiac MRI data that has been sorted.
